            title: `Query Methods — Derived Parsing, @Query, SpEL & Projections`,
            notes: `## Three Ways to Express a Query

1. **Derived** — method name parsed into a query (\`findByStatusAndTotalGreaterThan\`).
2. **\`@Query\`** — explicit JPQL, or \`nativeQuery=true\` SQL.
3. **\`@NamedQuery\`** — declared on the entity, referenced by \`<Entity>.<method>\` convention.

### The derived query parser (\`PartTree\`)

The parser splits the method name into a **subject** (\`find\`/\`read\`/\`get\`/\`query\`/\`stream\`/\`count\`/\`exists\`/\`delete\`) and a **predicate**. The predicate is tokenized on \`And\`/\`Or\`, with keywords mapping to JPQL operators.

\`\`\`mermaid
graph LR
  M["findByStatusAndTotalGreaterThanOrderByCreatedAtDesc"] --> S["Subject: find (limit none)"]
  M --> P["Predicate tree"]
  P --> A["Status = ?1"]
  P --> Bn["Total > ?2"]
  M --> O["OrderBy: createdAt DESC"]
\`\`\`

| Keyword | JPQL |
|---|---|
| \`Is\`, \`Equals\` | \`= ?\` |
| \`GreaterThanEqual\` / \`LessThan\` | \`>= / <\` |
| \`Between\` | \`between ?1 and ?2\` |
| \`Like\` / \`Containing\` / \`StartingWith\` | \`like\` (Containing wraps \`%x%\`) |
| \`In\` | \`in ?1\` |
| \`IsNull\` / \`IsNotNull\` | \`is null\` |
| \`True\` / \`False\` | \`= true\` |
| \`IgnoreCase\` | \`upper(x) = upper(?)\` |
| \`Top\`N / \`First\`N | limit |

> [!WARNING]
> Derived names rot. \`findByCustomerAddressCityAndStatusOrderByTotalDescCreatedAtAsc\` is unreadable and brittle — any property rename breaks it at startup. Past ~2 conditions, prefer \`@Query\` or a Specification. Property path traversal (\`CustomerAddressCity\`) also silently triggers **joins** — a hidden N+1/cartesian risk.

### @Query — JPQL, native, params, SpEL

\`\`\`mermaid
graph TB
  Q["@Query"] --> J["JPQL (default)<br/>portable, entity-oriented"]
  Q --> N["nativeQuery=true<br/>raw SQL, vendor-specific"]
  J --> NP["Named params :name<br/>@Param"]
  J --> PP["Positional ?1"]
  J --> SP["SpEL #{...}, ?#{...}"]
\`\`\`

> [!TIP]
> **Always prefer named parameters** (\`:status\` + \`@Param("status")\`) over positional \`?1\`. Positional binding breaks silently when you reorder method arguments; named binding is self-documenting and refactor-safe.

> [!DANGER]
> \`nativeQuery=true\` + \`Pageable\` requires a **separate \`countQuery\`** because Spring cannot derive a COUNT from arbitrary SQL. With native queries and dynamic sorting, \`Sort\` is **not** applied automatically the way it is for JPQL — you may need \`#{#pageable}\` SpEL or manual \`ORDER BY\`. Native + projections also bypass the dirty-checking/identity-map benefits of managed entities.

### Projections — return only what you need

| Type | How declared | Generates | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Interface (closed)** | interface with getters matching properties | Optimized SELECT of only those columns | Proxy-backed, read-only |
| **Interface (open)** | getter annotated \`@Value("#{target.x + target.y}")\` | Full entity SELECT, then SpEL | **Loses column pruning** — selects all |
| **DTO / class-based** | record/class with matching constructor | JPQL \`new com.x.Dto(...)\` or constructor mapping | Most explicit, immutable |
| **Dynamic** | generic \`<T> T findBy...(.., Class<T> type)\` | Caller chooses entity/interface/DTO at runtime | One method, many shapes |

> [!WARNING]
> **Closed interface projections prune columns; open projections do NOT.** The moment you add a \`@Value\`/SpEL getter, Spring must hydrate the full entity to evaluate it, issuing \`SELECT *\`. If you adopted projections for performance, an open projection silently defeats the purpose.

### Return types

| Return type | Meaning |
|---|---|
| \`Optional<T>\` | 0 or 1; throws \`IncorrectResultSizeDataAccessException\` if >1 |
| \`List<T>\` | 0..n |
| \`Stream<T>\` | Lazy cursor — **must close** (try-with-resources) and be inside an open tx |
| \`Page<T>\` | content + total count (extra COUNT query) |
| \`Slice<T>\` | content + hasNext (no COUNT) |
| \`Window<T>\` / \`ScrollPosition\` | Keyset scrolling (Spring Data 3.1+) |

> [!EU]
> When returning PII columns to UIs (GDPR data-minimisation), **closed DTO/interface projections are an architectural control**: the SQL physically does not select unneeded sensitive columns, so they never enter the JVM heap, logs, or serialized responses.`,
