            title: `Pagination & Sorting — Page vs Slice, the COUNT Trap & Keyset`,
            notes: `## Pageable, Sort and the Three Result Shapes

\`Pageable\` carries page number, size, and an embedded \`Sort\`. You pass it through from the controller; Spring Data appends \`ORDER BY\` + \`LIMIT/OFFSET\` and (for \`Page\`) fires a second COUNT.

| Shape | Extra COUNT? | Knows total? | Fetch strategy | Cost on big tables |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| \`List<T>\` + \`Pageable\` | No | No | LIMIT/OFFSET | Cheap, no metadata |
| \`Slice<T>\` | **No** | No (only \`hasNext()\`) | Fetches \`size+1\` rows | Cheap — preferred for infinite scroll |
| \`Page<T>\` | **Yes** | Yes (total elements/pages) | LIMIT/OFFSET + COUNT(*) | **Expensive** — COUNT scans |

\`\`\`mermaid
graph TB
  Req["Controller: Pageable(page=500,size=20)"] --> Repo["repository.findAll(pageable)"]
  Repo --> Q1["Data query:<br/>... ORDER BY id LIMIT 20 OFFSET 10000"]
  Repo --> Q2["COUNT query (Page only):<br/>SELECT count(*) ..."]
  Q1 --> DB["DB scans+discards 10000 rows<br/>then returns 20"]
  Q2 --> DB2["DB counts ALL matching rows"]
\`\`\`

### The COUNT(*) trap

> [!DANGER]
> Returning \`Page<T>\` on a multi-million-row table runs \`SELECT count(*)\` on **every page request**. On large or filtered tables this COUNT can dominate latency (full index/table scan) and often costs more than fetching the 20 rows. If the UI only needs "next/prev", return \`Slice<T>\` and skip the COUNT entirely.

### The OFFSET trap (deep pagination)

> [!DANGER]
> \`LIMIT 20 OFFSET 1000000\` forces the DB to **generate and discard** a million rows before returning 20. Offset pagination degrades **linearly with page depth** — page 50,000 is catastrophically slower than page 1. This is independent of indexes.

### Keyset (seek) pagination — the senior answer

Instead of "skip N rows", remember the **last seen key** and ask for "rows after this key". Constant time at any depth, but cannot jump to an arbitrary page number.

\`\`\`mermaid
graph LR
  O["OFFSET pagination<br/>WHERE ... ORDER BY id<br/>LIMIT 20 OFFSET 1_000_000"] -->|scans 1M rows| Slow["O(offset) — slow deep"]
  K["KEYSET pagination<br/>WHERE id > :lastSeenId<br/>ORDER BY id LIMIT 20"] -->|index seek| Fast["O(1) at any depth"]
\`\`\`

| | Offset | Keyset / Seek |
|---|---|---|
| Jump to arbitrary page | Yes | No (next/prev only) |
| Cost at depth | Degrades linearly | Constant (index seek) |
| Stable under concurrent inserts | No (rows shift) | Yes |
| Spring Data support | \`Pageable\`/\`Page\` | \`Window<T>\` + \`ScrollPosition.keyset()\` (3.1+) or manual \`WHERE id > ?\` |

> [!TIP]
> Spring Data 3.1+ adds **Scroll API**: \`WindowIterator\` / \`Window<T> scroll(ScrollPosition)\` with \`KeysetScrollPosition\`. It generates the \`WHERE (sortkey) > (lastValues)\` predicate for you and exposes \`window.positionAt(...)\` to continue. Use it instead of hand-rolling keyset SQL.

> [!SUCCESS]
> Pragmatic rule: **admin grids** that need page numbers → \`Page\` (accept the COUNT, ensure the WHERE is indexed). **Public/infinite-scroll feeds** → \`Slice\` or **keyset/Scroll**. Never deep-paginate a feed with offset.

### Sort safety

> [!WARNING]
> \`Sort\` property names are validated against the entity metamodel for derived/JPQL queries — but with **native queries** \`Sort\` is interpolated more loosely and is an **SQL injection surface** if built from raw user strings. Use \`Sort.by(allowlistedColumn)\`; consider \`JpaSort.unsafe(...)\` only for trusted expressions, never raw input.`,
