            title: `Joins In Depth — Types, Anti/Semi, Algorithms`,
            notes: `## Joins In Depth

A join builds a combined row source from two (or more) inputs. Mastery means knowing the **semantics** (which rows survive, which columns NULL-extend) *and* the **physical algorithms** the optimizer chooses.

### The Five Join Flavors

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart LR
  subgraph Inputs
    L[(Left L)]
    R[(Right R)]
  end
  L --> INNER["INNER<br/>matched only"]
  R --> INNER
  L --> LEFT["LEFT<br/>all L + matched R"]
  R --> LEFT
  L --> FULL["FULL<br/>all L + all R"]
  R --> FULL
  L --> CROSS["CROSS<br/>L × R (cartesian)"]
  R --> CROSS
\`\`\`

| Join | Keeps | Right cols when no match |
|------|-------|--------------------------|
| INNER | rows matching on both sides | (row excluded) |
| LEFT OUTER | all left rows | NULL-extended |
| RIGHT OUTER | all right rows | left NULL-extended |
| FULL OUTER | all rows from both | NULL-extended either side |
| CROSS | every L × R pair | n/a (no predicate) |

### ON vs WHERE on Outer Joins — The Classic Trap

\`\`\`sql
-- ❌ This silently becomes an INNER join!
-- The WHERE filter on a right-side column drops the NULL-extended rows.
SELECT c.name, o.amount
FROM customers c
LEFT JOIN orders o ON c.id = o.customer_id
WHERE o.status = 'COMPLETED';   -- NULL status rows fail predicate → dropped

-- ✅ Predicate belongs in the ON clause to preserve the outer side
SELECT c.name, o.amount
FROM customers c
LEFT JOIN orders o
  ON c.id = o.customer_id AND o.status = 'COMPLETED';
\`\`\`

> [!DANGER]
> Putting a condition on the **null-able side** of an outer join in WHERE turns it into an inner join. Filters on the *preserved* side belong in WHERE; filters on the *optional* side usually belong in ON.

### Self-Joins

\`\`\`sql
-- Employee → manager pairing (same table twice, two aliases)
SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager
FROM employees e
LEFT JOIN employees m ON e.manager_id = m.emp_id;
\`\`\`

### Anti-Joins — NOT EXISTS vs NOT IN (the NULL trap)

An **anti-join** returns rows from L that have *no* match in R.

\`\`\`sql
-- ✅ NOT EXISTS — NULL-safe, generally the optimal form
SELECT c.* FROM customers c
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT 1 FROM orders o WHERE o.customer_id = c.id
);

-- ⚠️ NOT IN — BROKEN if the subquery returns ANY NULL
SELECT c.* FROM customers c
WHERE c.id NOT IN (SELECT customer_id FROM orders);
-- If any customer_id is NULL, 'x NOT IN (.., NULL)' is UNKNOWN for EVERY x
-- → the whole query returns ZERO rows. A real production-incident classic.
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> \`x NOT IN (subquery)\` expands to \`x <> v1 AND x <> v2 AND ...\`. If any \`vi\` is NULL, that conjunct is UNKNOWN, the whole AND is UNKNOWN (never TRUE), and the row is dropped. **Prefer NOT EXISTS** for anti-joins. \`LEFT JOIN ... WHERE r.key IS NULL\` is also NULL-safe.

### Semi-Joins

A **semi-join** returns rows from L that have *at least one* match in R — but without duplicating L or pulling R's columns.

\`\`\`sql
-- EXISTS is a semi-join: stops at first match, no row multiplication
SELECT c.* FROM customers c
WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM orders o WHERE o.customer_id = c.id);

-- Contrast with INNER JOIN which DUPLICATES c per matching order:
SELECT DISTINCT c.* FROM customers c
JOIN orders o ON o.customer_id = c.id;   -- needs DISTINCT to dedupe
\`\`\`

### Join Algorithms (Conceptual)

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart TD
  Q{Optimizer<br/>picks based on<br/>size + indexes + stats}
  Q --> NL["Nested Loop<br/>for each L row, probe R<br/>great with index on R; O(N·M) without"]
  Q --> HJ["Hash Join<br/>build hash on smaller side,<br/>probe with larger; equi-joins; O(N+M)"]
  Q --> MJ["Merge Join<br/>sort both on key, zip together;<br/>great if already sorted; O(N log N + M log M)"]
\`\`\`

| Algorithm | Best when | Equality only? | Cost intuition |
|-----------|-----------|----------------|----------------|
| Nested loop | One side small, index on other side's key | No | rows(L) × cost(probe R) |
| Hash join | Large unsorted equi-join, fits in memory | Yes (equi) | build + probe, ~O(N+M) |
| Merge join | Inputs sorted on join key (index/ORDER) | Yes (range with care) | sort + linear merge |

> [!TIP]
> When an interviewer asks "your join is slow, why?": check (1) is it an equi-join? (2) is there an index on the probed key? (3) are stats current — a bad row estimate flips the optimizer to nested-loop over millions of rows (the classic "nested loop blow-up").`,
