            notes: `## Aggregation & GROUP BY

GROUP BY collapses many rows into one row per distinct grouping key; aggregate functions (COUNT, SUM, AVG, MIN, MAX) compute over each group.

### WHERE vs HAVING

| | WHERE | HAVING |
|--|-------|--------|
| Logical step | 3 (before grouping) | 5 (after grouping) |
| Operates on | individual rows | groups |
| Can use aggregates? | No | Yes |
| Performance | filters early (fewer rows to group) | filters late |

\`\`\`sql
-- Filter rows BEFORE grouping with WHERE (cheaper), filter GROUPS with HAVING
SELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) AS headcount, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal
FROM employees
WHERE hired_on >= DATE '2020-01-01'   -- row filter, runs first
GROUP BY dept_id
HAVING COUNT(*) >= 5;                  -- group filter, runs after aggregation
\`\`\`

> [!TIP]
> Push every predicate that doesn't need an aggregate into WHERE. Fewer rows enter the grouping operator, which means less hashing/sorting work.

### COUNT Pitfalls — The Interview Favorite

\`\`\`sql
SELECT
  COUNT(*)            AS all_rows,        -- counts rows, NULLs included
  COUNT(salary)       AS non_null_salary, -- IGNORES NULLs in salary
  COUNT(DISTINCT dept_id) AS n_depts,     -- distinct non-NULL values
  SUM(CASE WHEN salary > 100000 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS high_earners -- conditional count
FROM employees;
\`\`\`

> [!DANGER]
> \`COUNT(column)\` skips NULLs; \`COUNT(*)\` does not. After a LEFT JOIN, \`COUNT(o.order_id)\` correctly counts matched orders (0 for customers with none), but \`COUNT(*)\` would count the NULL-extended row as 1 — a textbook "every customer shows 1 order" bug.

### COUNT After Join — The Fan-Out Trap

\`\`\`sql
-- ❌ Joining orders AND items multiplies rows → SUM(amount) is inflated
SELECT c.id, SUM(o.amount), SUM(i.qty)
FROM customers c
JOIN orders o      ON o.customer_id = c.id
JOIN order_items i ON i.order_id   = o.order_id   -- fan-out!
GROUP BY c.id;
-- Each order's amount is repeated once per item → SUM(o.amount) too high.

-- ✅ Aggregate each branch independently first, then join
SELECT c.id, ord.total_amount, itm.total_qty
FROM customers c
LEFT JOIN (SELECT customer_id, SUM(amount) total_amount FROM orders GROUP BY customer_id) ord
       ON ord.customer_id = c.id
LEFT JOIN (SELECT o.customer_id, SUM(i.qty) total_qty
           FROM orders o JOIN order_items i ON i.order_id = o.order_id
           GROUP BY o.customer_id) itm
       ON itm.customer_id = c.id;
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> Joining two one-to-many relationships before aggregating causes **fan-out** (a cartesian explosion within each parent), inflating SUM/COUNT. Aggregate each branch in its own subquery, then join the pre-aggregated results.

### ROLLUP, CUBE, GROUPING SETS — Subtotals in One Pass

\`\`\`sql
-- ROLLUP: hierarchical subtotals (by region, by region+product, grand total)
SELECT region, product, SUM(amount)
FROM sales
GROUP BY ROLLUP (region, product);

-- CUBE: ALL combinations of subtotals
SELECT region, product, SUM(amount)
FROM sales
GROUP BY CUBE (region, product);

-- GROUPING SETS: explicitly list the groupings you want
SELECT region, product, SUM(amount)
FROM sales
GROUP BY GROUPING SETS ((region, product), (region), ());
\`\`\`

| Construct | Produces |
|-----------|----------|
| ROLLUP(a,b) | (a,b), (a), () — hierarchical |
| CUBE(a,b) | (a,b), (a), (b), () — all subsets |
| GROUPING SETS(...) | exactly the listed combinations |

> [!TIP]
> Use the \`GROUPING()\` function to distinguish a real NULL value from a subtotal placeholder NULL: \`GROUPING(region) = 1\` marks a subtotal row.

### Aggregates Ignore NULLs (Except COUNT(*))

\`\`\`sql
-- AVG over {100, NULL, 200} = 150, NOT 100.  NULLs are excluded entirely.
SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees;   -- denominator = count of non-NULL salaries
\`\`\`

> [!DANGER]
> \`AVG(col)\` divides by the count of **non-NULL** values, not total rows. If you want NULLs treated as zero, use \`AVG(COALESCE(col,0))\` — but be sure that's the business meaning.`,
