            title: `Window Functions — Ranking, LAG/LEAD, Frames`,
            notes: `## Window Functions

Window functions compute a value **across a set of rows related to the current row** without collapsing them — unlike GROUP BY, every input row is preserved.

### Anatomy

\`\`\`sql
function() OVER (
  PARTITION BY <cols>     -- reset the window per group (like GROUP BY but non-collapsing)
  ORDER BY <cols>         -- ordering within the partition (needed for ranking/running)
  <frame>                 -- ROWS/RANGE BETWEEN ... (the moving window)
)
\`\`\`

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart LR
  A[All rows kept] --> B{PARTITION BY}
  B --> C["ORDER BY<br/>within partition"]
  C --> D["FRAME<br/>ROWS BETWEEN..."]
  D --> E["window fn evaluated<br/>per row"]
\`\`\`

> [!TIP]
> Rule of thumb: GROUP BY answers "one number per group"; window functions answer "for each row, a number computed over its neighbors." If you need to keep detail rows *and* show an aggregate, you want a window function.

### Ranking: ROW_NUMBER vs RANK vs DENSE_RANK

\`\`\`sql
SELECT name, dept_id, salary,
  ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY dept_id ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rn,
  RANK()       OVER (PARTITION BY dept_id ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rnk,
  DENSE_RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY dept_id ORDER BY salary DESC) AS drnk
FROM employees;
\`\`\`

| Salaries (desc) | ROW_NUMBER | RANK | DENSE_RANK |
|-----------------|-----------|------|------------|
| 200 | 1 | 1 | 1 |
| 200 | 2 | 1 | 1 |
| 150 | 3 | 3 | 2 |
| 100 | 4 | 4 | 3 |

> [!WARNING]
> ROW_NUMBER is arbitrary among ties (add a tiebreaker for determinism). RANK leaves gaps after ties (1,1,3); DENSE_RANK does not (1,1,2). Pick based on whether "skipped ranks" is correct for your semantics.

### Top-N Per Group

\`\`\`sql
-- Highest-paid 2 employees per department
SELECT * FROM (
  SELECT name, dept_id, salary,
         ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY dept_id ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rn
  FROM employees
) t
WHERE rn <= 2;   -- can't filter the window fn directly → wrap in subquery
\`\`\`

> [!DANGER]
> You cannot put a window function in WHERE — windows are evaluated at SELECT (step 6), after WHERE (step 3). Always wrap in a subquery/CTE to filter on the result.

### LAG / LEAD — Row-to-Row Comparisons

\`\`\`sql
-- Month-over-month change
SELECT month, revenue,
  LAG(revenue)  OVER (ORDER BY month) AS prev_month,
  revenue - LAG(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY month) AS delta,
  LEAD(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY month) AS next_month
FROM monthly_revenue;
\`\`\`

### Running Totals & Moving Averages — The Frame Clause

\`\`\`sql
-- Running total: frame = start of partition to current row
SELECT ordered_at, amount,
  SUM(amount) OVER (ORDER BY ordered_at
                    ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) AS running_total
FROM orders;

-- 7-row moving average (current + 6 preceding)
SELECT ordered_at, amount,
  AVG(amount) OVER (ORDER BY ordered_at
                    ROWS BETWEEN 6 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) AS moving_avg_7
FROM orders;
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> **ROWS vs RANGE**: \`ROWS\` counts physical rows; \`RANGE\` groups by peer values of the ORDER BY key (all ties share a frame). With \`ORDER BY\` and no explicit frame, the default is \`RANGE UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\` — which can surprise you when there are duplicate ORDER BY values (the running total jumps over all peers at once). Specify \`ROWS\` for a strict row-by-row running total.

### Other Useful Window Functions

| Function | Use |
|----------|-----|
| NTILE(n) | bucket rows into n quantiles (quartiles, percentiles) |
| FIRST_VALUE / LAST_VALUE | value at frame boundary |
| NTH_VALUE(expr, n) | nth value in frame |
| PERCENT_RANK / CUME_DIST | relative rank / cumulative distribution |`,
