              {
                q: `Window function vs GROUP BY?`,
                a: `GROUP BY collapses rows into one per group. A window function computes an aggregate/rank over related rows but keeps every input row. Use windows when you need detail rows and an aggregate together.`
              },
              {
                q: `ROW_NUMBER vs RANK vs DENSE_RANK?`,
                a: `ROW_NUMBER assigns unique sequential numbers (arbitrary among ties). RANK gives ties the same rank then skips (1,1,3). DENSE_RANK gives ties the same rank with no gaps (1,1,2).`
              },
              {
                q: `Why can't you filter a window function in WHERE?`,
                a: `Windows are evaluated at the SELECT step (6), after WHERE (3). Wrap the query in a subquery/CTE and filter the computed column in the outer query.`
              },
              {
                q: `How do you get top-N rows per group?`,
                a: `Compute ROW_NUMBER() (or RANK) PARTITION BY group ORDER BY metric DESC in a subquery, then filter rn <= N in the outer query.`
              },
              {
                q: `What do LAG and LEAD do?`,
                a: `LAG returns a value from a preceding row, LEAD from a following row, within the ordered partition. Used for deltas, period-over-period comparisons, and detecting changes between consecutive rows.`
              },
              {
                q: `How do you compute a running total?`,
                a: `SUM(x) OVER (ORDER BY k ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW). Use ROWS (not RANGE) to avoid jumping over peer ties.`
              },
              {
                q: `ROWS vs RANGE in a frame?`,
                a: `ROWS counts physical rows relative to the current row. RANGE groups by peer values of the ORDER BY key, so all rows with equal ordering values share a frame. Default with ORDER BY is RANGE ... CURRENT ROW.`
              },
              {
                q: `Why does LAST_VALUE often return the current row's value?`,
                a: `The default frame is UNBOUNDED PRECEDING to CURRENT ROW, so the "last" value is the current one. Specify ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING.`
              },
              {
                q: `What is NTILE used for?`,
                a: `Dividing ordered rows into n roughly equal buckets — quartiles, deciles, percentile bucketing. Earlier buckets get the extra row when the count is not evenly divisible.`
              },
              {
                q: `How do you deduplicate rows keeping one per key?`,
                a: `ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY key ORDER BY tiebreaker), then keep rn = 1 in an outer query. Choose the ORDER BY to define which duplicate survives (e.g., newest).`
              },
              {
                q: `Does PARTITION BY require ORDER BY?`,
                a: `No. PARTITION BY alone gives a per-partition aggregate over the whole partition (e.g., dept average on every row). ORDER BY is needed for ranking, LAG/LEAD, and frame-based running calculations.`
              },
              {
                q: `Can you reference one window function inside another?`,
                a: `Not directly in the same SELECT level. Nest via a subquery/CTE: compute the first window result, then apply the second window over it.`
              }
