            title: `Subqueries & CTEs — Correlation, Recursion, Materialization`,
            notes: `## Subqueries & CTEs

### Correlated vs Non-Correlated

\`\`\`sql
-- NON-correlated: inner query is independent, evaluated once
SELECT * FROM employees
WHERE salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees);

-- CORRELATED: inner query references the outer row → conceptually re-evaluated per row
SELECT e.* FROM employees e
WHERE salary > (SELECT AVG(salary) FROM employees x WHERE x.dept_id = e.dept_id);
\`\`\`

> [!TIP]
> "Conceptually per row" — modern optimizers frequently **decorrelate** a correlated subquery into a join/group-by. Don't assume O(N) round trips; assume the planner may rewrite it. But poorly-shaped correlated subqueries (no supporting index) genuinely do run per row.

### Derived Tables (Inline Subquery in FROM)

\`\`\`sql
SELECT d.dept_id, d.avg_sal
FROM (SELECT dept_id, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal FROM employees GROUP BY dept_id) d
WHERE d.avg_sal > 60000;
\`\`\`

### CTEs (Common Table Expressions)

\`\`\`sql
WITH dept_avg AS (
  SELECT dept_id, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal FROM employees GROUP BY dept_id
),
big_depts AS (
  SELECT dept_id FROM dept_avg WHERE avg_sal > 60000
)
SELECT e.* FROM employees e JOIN big_depts b ON e.dept_id = b.dept_id;
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> **Materialization matters.** Historically PostgreSQL always materialized CTEs (an optimization fence — sometimes a footgun, sometimes a useful hint). Since PG12, non-recursive CTEs referenced once are inlined unless you write \`WITH x AS MATERIALIZED (...)\`. SQL Server/Oracle generally inline CTEs as views. Know your engine: a CTE is not automatically a temp table.

### Recursive CTEs — Hierarchies & Sequences

\`\`\`sql
-- Walk an org chart from a given manager downward
WITH RECURSIVE org AS (
  -- anchor: the starting node(s)
  SELECT emp_id, name, manager_id, 1 AS depth
  FROM employees WHERE emp_id = 1
  UNION ALL
  -- recursive term: join the CTE back to the base table
  SELECT e.emp_id, e.name, e.manager_id, o.depth + 1
  FROM employees e
  JOIN org o ON e.manager_id = o.emp_id
)
SELECT * FROM org ORDER BY depth, emp_id;
\`\`\`

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart TD
  A["Anchor query<br/>(seed rows)"] --> U{UNION ALL}
  U --> R["Recursive query<br/>joins CTE to base"]
  R --> W["Working table<br/>(rows from last iteration)"]
  W -->|non-empty| R
  W -->|empty| DONE["Stop → union of all iterations"]
\`\`\`

> [!DANGER]
> A recursive CTE with a cycle in the data (A manages B manages A) loops forever. Guard with a depth limit, a visited-path array (PostgreSQL \`CYCLE\` clause), or \`UNION\` (not \`UNION ALL\`) to dedupe. Always cap recursion depth on untrusted hierarchies.

### When To Use Which

| Need | Reach for |
|------|-----------|
| Reuse a result set, readability | CTE |
| One-off inline grouping | Derived table |
| Per-row existence check | Correlated EXISTS |
| Hierarchy / graph / number series | Recursive CTE |
| Filter on an aggregate of the whole table | Non-correlated scalar subquery |

> [!SUCCESS]
> For senior interviews: a CTE improves *readability* but is not inherently faster than the equivalent subquery/join — and on some engines a materialized CTE blocks predicate pushdown, making it slower. Choose for clarity, then verify with EXPLAIN.`,
