            flashcards: [
              {
                q: `Correlated vs non-correlated subquery?`,
                a: `A non-correlated subquery is independent of the outer query and evaluated once. A correlated subquery references outer-row columns and is conceptually evaluated per outer row, though optimizers often decorrelate it into a join.`
              },
              {
                q: `What is a derived table?`,
                a: `A subquery in the FROM clause that acts as an inline, unnamed (or aliased) result set. It must be aliased and exists only for that query, unlike a CTE which is named at the top.`
              },
              {
                q: `Is a CTE always materialized into a temp table?`,
                a: `No. It is engine-dependent. PostgreSQL <12 always materialized (an optimization fence); PG12+ inlines single-reference non-recursive CTEs unless marked MATERIALIZED. SQL Server/Oracle generally inline them.`
              },
              {
                q: `How does a recursive CTE work?`,
                a: `An anchor query seeds the working table; the recursive term joins the CTE to base data via UNION ALL, repeatedly feeding new rows back until it produces no new rows; the result is the union of all iterations.`
              },
              {
                q: `How do you prevent infinite loops in a recursive CTE?`,
                a: `Add a depth counter with a limit, use UNION (dedupes) instead of UNION ALL, or use a cycle-detection mechanism (PostgreSQL CYCLE clause / visited-path array) for cyclic data.`
              },
              {
                q: `Is a CTE faster than the equivalent subquery?`,
                a: `Not inherently. It mainly aids readability. A materialized CTE can be slower because it blocks predicate pushdown and join reordering. Always verify with EXPLAIN.`
              },
              {
                q: `When is a correlated EXISTS preferable to a join?`,
                a: `For semi/anti-join existence checks where you do not want row multiplication or right-side columns. EXISTS short-circuits at the first match and is NULL-safe, unlike IN/NOT IN.`
              },
              {
                q: `How do you generate a number or date series without a helper table?`,
                a: `A recursive CTE: anchor with the first value, recursive term increments until a bound. Useful for date spines, gap-filling, and exploding ranges.`
              },
              {
                q: `What is an optimization fence and how do CTEs relate?`,
                a: `A boundary the optimizer will not push predicates across or reorder. A materialized CTE acts as a fence: the inner query is computed as written, which can help (compute-once reuse) or hurt (no pushdown).`
              },
              {
                q: `When should you choose a CTE over a derived table?`,
                a: `When the result is referenced multiple times or readability of a multi-step query matters. A derived table is fine for a single inline use. Recursion requires a CTE.`
              },
              {
                q: `Why might a scalar non-correlated subquery be efficient?`,
                a: `It is evaluated exactly once and cached as a constant for the whole query (e.g., comparing each row to a global AVG), so it adds negligible repeated cost.`
              }
            ]
