            title: `Practical Patterns & Correctness — Pagination, Upserts, NULLs, Puzzles`,
            notes: `## Practical Patterns & Correctness

### Pagination: Keyset vs OFFSET

\`\`\`sql
-- ❌ OFFSET pagination: the DB still scans and discards all skipped rows.
-- Page 10,000 means reading ~1,000,000 rows then throwing them away.
SELECT * FROM orders ORDER BY ordered_at DESC, order_id DESC
LIMIT 100 OFFSET 1000000;

-- ✅ Keyset (seek) pagination: remember the last seen key, seek past it.
SELECT * FROM orders
WHERE (ordered_at, order_id) < (:last_ts, :last_id)   -- row-value comparison
ORDER BY ordered_at DESC, order_id DESC
LIMIT 100;
\`\`\`

| | OFFSET | Keyset / Seek |
|--|--------|---------------|
| Cost of deep pages | O(offset) — scans skipped rows | O(log n) via index seek |
| Stable under inserts? | No (rows shift, dupes/skips) | Yes (anchored to a key) |
| Random page jump? | Yes | No (sequential only) |
| Needs unique tiebreaker? | No | Yes (to be deterministic) |

> [!TIP]
> Keyset pagination needs a **total order** — append a unique column (usually the PK) to the ORDER BY so ties don't cause skipped/duplicated rows across pages. Use a row-value comparison \`(a,b) < (:a,:b)\` so the index can drive the seek.

### Upserts: ON CONFLICT vs MERGE

\`\`\`sql
-- PostgreSQL / SQLite: INSERT ... ON CONFLICT
INSERT INTO inventory (sku, qty) VALUES ('A1', 5)
ON CONFLICT (sku) DO UPDATE SET qty = inventory.qty + EXCLUDED.qty;

-- MySQL
INSERT INTO inventory (sku, qty) VALUES ('A1', 5)
ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE qty = qty + VALUES(qty);

-- ANSI / SQL Server / Oracle: MERGE
MERGE INTO inventory t
USING (SELECT 'A1' AS sku, 5 AS qty) s ON t.sku = s.sku
WHEN MATCHED     THEN UPDATE SET t.qty = t.qty + s.qty
WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN INSERT (sku, qty) VALUES (s.sku, s.qty);
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> MERGE has historically had **concurrency/uniqueness race conditions** (notably SQL Server) and is not atomic against concurrent inserts without proper isolation/constraints. ON CONFLICT relies on a unique constraint and is atomic at the row level. Always have the unique index that the conflict target references.

### NULL Semantics & Three-Valued Logic

\`\`\`sql
NULL = NULL          -- UNKNOWN (not TRUE!)
NULL <> 1            -- UNKNOWN
NULL IS NULL         -- TRUE  (use IS NULL / IS NOT NULL)
1 = NULL OR 1 = 1    -- TRUE  (TRUE OR UNKNOWN = TRUE)
1 = NULL AND 1 = 1   -- UNKNOWN (UNKNOWN AND TRUE = UNKNOWN)
COALESCE(NULL, 0)    -- 0  (first non-NULL)
NULLIF(a, b)         -- NULL if a=b else a
\`\`\`

| A | B | A AND B | A OR B |
|---|---|---------|--------|
| T | U | U | T |
| F | U | F | U |
| U | U | U | U |

> [!DANGER]
> \`x = NULL\` is never TRUE — use \`IS NULL\`. DISTINCT and GROUP BY treat all NULLs as **equal** to each other (they group together), but a UNIQUE constraint typically treats NULLs as **distinct** (multiple NULLs allowed). These inconsistent rules trip up even experienced engineers.

### Set Operations

\`\`\`sql
SELECT id FROM a UNION     SELECT id FROM b;   -- distinct union
SELECT id FROM a UNION ALL SELECT id FROM b;   -- keep duplicates (cheaper, no sort/hash)
SELECT id FROM a INTERSECT SELECT id FROM b;   -- in both
SELECT id FROM a EXCEPT    SELECT id FROM b;   -- in a, not in b (MINUS in Oracle)
\`\`\`

> [!TIP]
> Prefer \`UNION ALL\` unless you actually need de-duplication — \`UNION\` adds a distinct/sort step. Set operators compare full rows by position and treat NULLs as equal, so they're a NULL-safe alternative to NOT IN for set difference (EXCEPT).

### Interview SQL Puzzles

#### 2nd Highest Salary

\`\`\`sql
-- Window approach (handles ties cleanly, generalizes to Nth)
SELECT DISTINCT salary FROM (
  SELECT salary, DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS r FROM employees
) t WHERE r = 2;

-- Without window functions
SELECT MAX(salary) FROM employees
WHERE salary < (SELECT MAX(salary) FROM employees);
\`\`\`

#### Gaps & Islands (consecutive runs)

\`\`\`sql
-- Group consecutive integers/dates into 'islands'
-- Trick: (value - row_number) is CONSTANT within a consecutive run
SELECT MIN(d) AS island_start, MAX(d) AS island_end, COUNT(*) AS len
FROM (
  SELECT d,
    d - (ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY d)) * INTERVAL '1 day' AS grp
  FROM login_days
) t
GROUP BY grp
ORDER BY island_start;
\`\`\`

#### Deduplicate Keeping One Row

\`\`\`sql
WITH ranked AS (
  SELECT ctid,  -- PostgreSQL physical row id; use PK elsewhere
         ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY email ORDER BY id) AS rn
  FROM users
)
DELETE FROM users WHERE ctid IN (SELECT ctid FROM ranked WHERE rn > 1);
\`\`\`

> [!SUCCESS]
> The "value minus dense rank/row number is constant" identity powers gaps-&-islands and is one of the highest-signal window-function tricks in senior interviews. Be able to derive it on the spot.`,
