            title: `Other Index Types & Trade-offs: Hash, GIN/GiST, BRIN, Partial, Expression`,
            notes: `## Beyond B+Tree — pick the structure that fits the access pattern

B+Tree is the default, but the right index type can turn an impossible query into an instant one. Senior interviews probe whether you know *when each applies* and the **write cost** they impose.

### Index types at a glance (PostgreSQL-centric, with analogues)

| Type | Supports | Great for | Cannot do | Notes |
|------|----------|-----------|-----------|-------|
| **B-Tree** (default) | \`=\`, \`<\`, \`>\`, \`BETWEEN\`, \`LIKE 'x%'\`, sort, \`MIN\`/\`MAX\` | almost everything | substring / containment | the workhorse |
| **Hash** | \`=\` only | pure equality on large keys | ranges, sorting | Postgres 10+ WAL-logged & crash-safe; rarely beats B-Tree, so seldom worth it |
| **GIN** (inverted) | containment: \`@>\`, \`?\`, \`@@\`, array/JSONB ops | full-text, JSONB, arrays, \`pg_trgm\` LIKE/regex | range/sort on the base value | many keys → one row; **slow to update**, fast to read; \`fastupdate\` pending list |
| **GiST** (balanced, extensible) | overlap/nearest: geometry, ranges, KNN \`<->\` | geospatial (PostGIS), range types, nearest-neighbour | exact text equality | lossy; great for "what's near / overlaps" |
| **SP-GiST** | non-balanced partitioning | quadtrees, tries, IP/prefix | — | niche |
| **BRIN** (block-range) | \`>\`, \`<\`, range on **naturally-ordered** data | huge append-only tables (time-series, logs) by timestamp | random/unsorted data | tiny (stores min/max per block range); near-zero maintenance |

### Hash indexes — usually a trap

A hash index gives O(1) equality lookup, but B+Tree equality is already ~O(log_fanout n) ≈ 3 reads, the hash index can't do ranges/sorts/prefix, and historically wasn't crash-safe. **Default to B-Tree.** Consider hash only for very large, long, equality-only keys where the B-Tree's larger size hurts cache — a rare case.

### GIN — full-text, JSONB, arrays, trigram LIKE

GIN is an **inverted index**: it maps each *element* (a word, a JSONB key/value, an array element, a trigram) to the list of rows containing it. That makes "does this document contain X" and "does this JSONB contain that" fast.

\`\`\`sql
-- JSONB containment:
CREATE INDEX idx_doc_gin ON docs USING gin (data jsonb_path_ops);
SELECT * FROM docs WHERE data @> '{"status":"active"}';
-- Full-text:
CREATE INDEX idx_fts ON articles USING gin (to_tsvector('english', body));
SELECT * FROM articles WHERE to_tsvector('english', body) @@ plainto_tsquery('postgres index');
-- Trigram LIKE (defeats leading wildcard!):
CREATE EXTENSION pg_trgm;
CREATE INDEX idx_name_trgm ON users USING gin (name gin_trgm_ops);
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name LIKE '%son%';   -- now indexable
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> **GIN writes are expensive.** Inserting one row may touch many posting lists. The \`fastupdate\` option buffers changes in a pending list (faster writes, slower reads until merged). For write-heavy JSONB, weigh the index cost; for read-heavy, GIN is transformative.

### BRIN — the index for time-series and logs

BRIN stores only the **min/max value per block range** (default 128 pages). For a 1-billion-row, append-ordered \`events\` table by \`created_at\`, a BRIN index is **kilobytes** (vs gigabytes for a B-Tree) and lets a range query skip block ranges whose min/max can't match. The catch: it only works when **physical order correlates with the column** (naturally true for append-only timestamp/ID columns). On randomly-ordered data it's useless.

\`\`\`sql
CREATE INDEX idx_events_brin ON events USING brin (created_at);  -- tiny, near-free to maintain
\`\`\`

### Partial indexes — index only the rows you query

A **partial index** has a \`WHERE\` clause: it indexes only matching rows. Smaller, faster, cheaper to maintain — perfect for skewed data where you only query a minority.

\`\`\`sql
-- Only 2% of orders are 'PENDING' but that's all the worker queries:
CREATE INDEX idx_pending ON orders (created_at) WHERE status = 'PENDING';
-- Enforce a partial uniqueness (one active subscription per user):
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX uq_active_sub ON subs (user_id) WHERE active;
\`\`\`

### Expression (functional) indexes — index a computed value

\`\`\`sql
CREATE INDEX idx_lower_email ON users (lower(email));          -- case-insensitive seeks
CREATE INDEX idx_order_month ON orders (date_trunc('month', created_at));
\`\`\`
The query's expression must match the index expression exactly to be used.

### Write amplification — the cost of too many indexes

> [!DANGER]
> **Every index is a copy of (some of) your data that must be maintained on every write.** An \`INSERT\` updates the heap **and every index**. An \`UPDATE\` of an indexed column updates the heap and those indexes (in Postgres, a non-HOT update touches *all* indexes). So N indexes ≈ N× the write work, N× the WAL, more lock contention, more cache pressure, longer \`VACUUM\`, slower bulk loads, and bigger backups. A table with 12 indexes can have its insert throughput cut by 5–10×.

**Rules of thumb:** index for the queries you actually run (check \`pg_stat_user_indexes\` for unused ones and drop them), prefer fewer composite/covering indexes over many single-column ones, and remember **read speed and write speed trade off through the index count**.

> [!SUCCESS]
> **Senior soundbite:** "Default to B-Tree. Reach for GIN when the predicate is containment — full-text, JSONB \`@>\`, arrays, or trigram LIKE that defeats a leading wildcard. Reach for BRIN on huge append-only time-series where physical order tracks the column — kilobytes instead of gigabytes. Use partial indexes for skewed data and expression indexes for computed predicates. And I count my indexes: each one taxes every write, so I drop the unused ones."`,
