            notes: `## Anti-Patterns & Scaling Reads

The last mile: the recurring SQL anti-patterns that defeat indexes, and the architectural moves (denormalization, materialized views, read replicas) when indexing alone isn't enough.

### Query anti-patterns that defeat indexes

| Anti-pattern | Why it hurts | Better |
|--------------|--------------|--------|
| **\`SELECT *\`** | drags every column over the wire, **breaks index-only scans** (index doesn't cover unneeded columns → heap fetch), bloats cache, breaks on schema change | select only the columns you use |
| **Implicit conversion** | \`WHERE phone = 123\` on a \`VARCHAR\` casts the column → non-SARGable seq scan (silent in MySQL) | match literal types to column types |
| **\`OR\` across columns** | \`WHERE a=? OR b=?\` often can't use one composite index; may seq-scan | \`UNION\`/\`UNION ALL\` of two SARGable queries, or rely on BitmapOr of two indexes |
| **Functions on columns** | \`WHERE year(d)=2026\` non-SARGable | range predicate or expression index |
| **Leading wildcard** | \`LIKE '%x'\` can't seek | trigram/full-text index |
| **\`NOT IN\` / \`<>\`** | usually unindexable; \`NOT IN\` with NULLs is also a correctness trap | rethink; \`NOT EXISTS\`, anti-join |
| **Over-fetching, no \`LIMIT\`** | materializes huge result sets | paginate (keyset) |
| **Over-indexing** | every index taxes writes (§4) | index for real queries; drop unused |

### \`OR\` vs \`UNION\` — the classic rewrite

\`\`\`sql
-- May seq-scan (one index can't satisfy both sides cleanly):
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1 OR phone = $2;
-- Two SARGable seeks combined (each uses its own index):
SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1
UNION
SELECT * FROM users WHERE phone = $2;   -- UNION dedups; UNION ALL if disjoint & faster
\`\`\`
(PostgreSQL's planner can also do a \`BitmapOr\` of the two indexes, so always check \`EXPLAIN\` before rewriting — modern planners sometimes handle the \`OR\` fine.)

### Index bloat (PostgreSQL MVCC)

> [!WARNING]
> Under MVCC, \`UPDATE\`/\`DELETE\` leave **dead tuples**; indexes accumulate dead entries until \`VACUUM\` reclaims them. A heavily-churned index can grow far past its live size (**bloat**), slowing scans and wasting cache. Symptoms: index much larger than expected, slow index scans. Fix: keep **autovacuum** healthy, and **\`REINDEX CONCURRENTLY\`** (PG12+) to rebuild a bloated index without a long lock.

### When to denormalize

Normalization (3NF) is the default — it prevents update anomalies. **Denormalize deliberately** when a read path is hot and the join cost is the bottleneck:
- **Pre-computed aggregates / counters** (\`comment_count\` on \`posts\`) to avoid counting on every read — but now you own consistency (triggers, app logic, or eventual reconciliation).
- **Duplicated columns** to avoid a join on a hot path (\`order.customer_name\`) — accept the write-time fan-out to keep it in sync.
- Rule: **denormalize for reads you can't otherwise make fast, and only after measuring.** You're trading write complexity and consistency risk for read speed.

### Materialized views — cache an expensive query

A **materialized view** stores the *result* of a query physically; reads hit the cached result, not the underlying joins/aggregates.

\`\`\`sql
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW daily_sales AS
SELECT date_trunc('day', created_at) AS day, sum(amount) AS total, count(*) AS n
FROM orders GROUP BY 1;
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX ON daily_sales (day);          -- enables CONCURRENTLY refresh + fast lookups
REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY daily_sales; -- rebuild without blocking reads (needs unique idx)
\`\`\`
Trade-off: data is **stale** between refreshes. Great for dashboards/reports where minutes-old data is fine; wrong for must-be-current reads.

### Covering-index design for a real query (worked example)

\`\`\`sql
-- The hot query (an "orders dashboard for a customer"):
SELECT id, status, amount, created_at
FROM   orders
WHERE  customer_id = $1 AND status = 'PAID'
ORDER  BY created_at DESC
LIMIT  20;
\`\`\`
**Design it deterministically:**
1. **Equality seek columns first:** \`customer_id\`, \`status\`.
2. **Sort column next** (so ORDER BY needs no Sort node, and LIMIT stops early): \`created_at DESC\`.
3. **Cover the output** (\`id\`, \`amount\`) via \`INCLUDE\` so it's an **index-only scan** — zero heap fetches.

\`\`\`sql
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_dash
  ON orders (customer_id, status, created_at DESC)
  INCLUDE (amount);     -- id is the PK, already in the heap ptr; amount rides along
-- Result: Index Only Scan, Index Cond (customer_id, status), pre-sorted, LIMIT 20 stops at 20 rows.
\`\`\`

### Scaling reads beyond one box

When a single primary can't keep up with read load even with perfect indexes:
- **Read replicas** — route read-only traffic to async followers; accept **replication lag** (read-your-writes anomalies → route the user's own reads to the primary or use synchronous/quorum reads for critical paths).
- **Caching** (Redis) in front of hot read paths — now own invalidation.
- **Partitioning / sharding** — split a giant table by range/hash so each shard's indexes are smaller and hotter in cache.
- **Materialized views / CQRS read models** — maintain a denormalized read-optimised projection.

> [!SUCCESS]
> **Senior soundbite:** "First make the query SARGable and give it the right composite/covering index — usually that's the whole fix. \`SELECT *\` and \`OR\`-across-columns are the two anti-patterns I check immediately. For an expensive aggregate that doesn't need to be current, a materialized view with a unique index and \`REFRESH ... CONCURRENTLY\`. I denormalize only for a measured hot read path and only after accepting the consistency cost. Beyond one box: read replicas with explicit handling of replication lag, then partitioning."`,
