            notes: `# Locks, deadlocks, and the two locking philosophies

Even MVCC engines lock for **writes** and for explicit \`FOR UPDATE\` reads. Understanding lock modes, granularity, deadlocks, and the optimistic/pessimistic split is core senior material.

## Lock modes & granularity

| Mode | Compatible with | Used for |
|---|---|---|
| **Shared (S)** | other S | reads under 2PL / \`FOR SHARE\` |
| **Exclusive (X)** | nothing | writes / \`FOR UPDATE\` |

| Granularity | Pro | Con |
|---|---|---|
| Row lock | high concurrency | many locks → memory/bookkeeping |
| Table lock | cheap, few locks | kills concurrency |
| **Gap / next-key** (InnoDB) | blocks phantoms | surprising deadlocks |

**Next-key lock** (InnoDB) = a row lock + a **gap lock** on the range *before* it. It locks the gap so no other txn can INSERT a phantom into the range — this is how InnoDB REPEATABLE READ prevents phantoms. Gap locks are a frequent source of "mysterious" deadlocks because they lock ranges, not just rows.

> [!WARNING]
> Gap locks make INSERTs conflict with one another even when no row collides, because two INSERTs into the same gap both want it. Range-scan + insert workloads under InnoDB RR deadlock far more than people expect. If you don't need phantom protection, READ COMMITTED disables most gap locking.

---

## Deadlocks

A deadlock is a cycle in the **waits-for** graph: T1 holds A and wants B; T2 holds B and wants A. Neither can proceed.

\`\`\`mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  participant T1
  participant A as Row A
  participant B as Row B
  participant T2
  T1->>A: lock A (X)
  T2->>B: lock B (X)
  T1->>B: wait for B  (held by T2)
  T2->>A: wait for A  (held by T1)
  Note over T1,T2: cycle → deadlock; engine aborts one victim
\`\`\`

Engines **detect** deadlocks (build the waits-for graph, find a cycle) and **abort a victim** (Postgres: error 40P01; MySQL: 1213) — the chosen victim's transaction rolls back and must retry.

### Avoidance & mitigation
- **Lock ordering** — always acquire locks in a consistent global order (e.g. by primary key ascending). If every txn locks rows in the same order, no cycle can form. This is the #1 practical fix.
- **Keep transactions short** — less time holding locks = smaller deadlock window.
- **Lower isolation / READ COMMITTED** — fewer/looser locks (no gap locks) means fewer deadlock shapes.
- **Lock at coarse grain up front** — grab everything you need at the start (deadlock-avoidance via no incremental acquisition), at the cost of concurrency.
- **\`SELECT … FOR UPDATE NOWAIT\` / \`… SKIP LOCKED\`** — fail fast or skip rather than queueing into a deadlock.

> [!TIP]
> When you see intermittent 40001/40P01/1213 errors, the right answer is usually NOT "raise lock timeouts." It's (1) enforce a consistent lock acquisition order, (2) shorten transactions, and (3) add an application-level retry-on-deadlock loop. Deadlocks at low rate are normal; the app must tolerate them.

### Lock escalation
Some engines (SQL Server, DB2) **escalate** many row locks into a single table lock once a threshold is crossed, trading concurrency for lock-manager memory. **Postgres and InnoDB do not do lock escalation** — a common interview gotcha. (Postgres can run out of shared-lock memory instead; InnoDB keeps row locks.)

---

## Optimistic vs Pessimistic locking

| | **Pessimistic** (\`SELECT … FOR UPDATE\`) | **Optimistic** (\`@Version\` column) |
|---|---|---|
| Assumes | conflicts are likely | conflicts are rare |
| Mechanism | acquire lock, block others up front | check a version/timestamp at write time |
| Cost when no conflict | lock overhead + reduced concurrency | ~free (one extra WHERE clause) |
| Cost when conflict | waiting/blocking | wasted work + retry (OptimisticLockException) |
| Deadlock risk | yes | no (no held locks) |
| Best for | hot rows, high contention, long critical sections | low-contention, read-mostly, stateless web tier |

**Optimistic** mechanism: add a \`version\` (or timestamp) column. On UPDATE, the WHERE clause includes the version you read; you bump it. If another txn already bumped it, your UPDATE matches **zero rows** → you detect the lost update and retry/abort.

\`\`\`sql
UPDATE account SET balance = ?, version = version + 1
WHERE id = ? AND version = ?;   -- 0 rows affected => someone else won => OptimisticLockException
\`\`\`

> [!SUCCESS]
> JPA/Hibernate \`@Version\` does exactly this automatically. The win: no DB locks held across the (possibly long) user think-time of a web request, so it scales horizontally. The cost: under real contention you burn retries — at which point pessimistic (or a queue) wins.

> [!DANGER]
> Optimistic locking **only protects the entity it versions.** It does not stop write skew across *different* rows or invariants that span rows — for those you still need FOR UPDATE on the relevant rows or SERIALIZABLE.
`,
