            title: `5. Practical: Choosing Levels, Retries, Queues & Spring @Transactional`,
            notes: `# Putting it to work

Theory meets the codebase here: which level to pick, how to retry, idempotency, long-transaction cost, the SKIP LOCKED queue, and how all of it maps onto Spring.

## Choosing an isolation level

> [!TIP]
> Default to **READ COMMITTED** (the Postgres default; Oracle's default). Reach for stronger only when a specific invariant demands it:
> - **REPEATABLE READ / Snapshot** when one transaction must see a stable snapshot across many reads (reports, multi-statement reads that must agree).
> - **SERIALIZABLE** when correctness depends on an invariant that spans rows and could suffer write skew (booking systems, balance/quota rules, "at least one" constraints) — and you can afford retries.
>
> MySQL's default is REPEATABLE READ; many teams set it to READ COMMITTED to reduce gap-lock deadlocks. Know your engine's default — it's a favourite probe.

## Retry on serialization failure

SERIALIZABLE (SSI) and Postgres RR can abort with **serialization_failure (40001)** or **deadlock (40P01)**. These are *expected, retryable* errors — wrap the transaction in a bounded retry loop with backoff. The operation **must be safe to re-run**, which leads straight to idempotency.

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[BEGIN txn] --> B[do work]
  B --> C{commit}
  C -->|ok| Z[done]
  C -->|40001 / 40P01| D{retries left?}
  D -->|yes| E[backoff + jitter] --> A
  D -->|no| F[give up, surface error]
\`\`\`

## Idempotent writes

If you retry, you must not double-apply. Techniques:
- **Natural idempotency** — \`SET status='PAID'\` is idempotent; \`balance = balance + 100\` is not.
- **Idempotency key** — a unique \`request_id\` with \`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING\`; the duplicate retry no-ops.
- **Upsert** — \`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (key) DO UPDATE\`.

> [!SUCCESS]
> Retry + idempotency are a package deal. Any system using SERIALIZABLE or at-least-once messaging needs both. An idempotency key table is the single most reliable pattern.

## Long transactions are expensive

> [!DANGER]
> A long-running transaction is a system-wide tax, not a local cost:
> - **Postgres**: pins the vacuum horizon → bloat, eventually XID-wraparound risk; holds locks longer → more contention/deadlocks.
> - **InnoDB**: grows the undo history list → slower reads, bigger storage.
> - Connection held = one fewer in the pool. "idle in transaction" is a code smell.
>
> Never do network calls, user think-time, or large batch work inside an open DB transaction. Keep transactions to the minimal write critical section.

## SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED — the queue pattern

A production-grade way to build a work queue / job dispatcher on a relational DB: multiple workers each grab a batch of *unlocked* pending rows, skipping rows other workers already hold. No external queue needed.

\`\`\`sql
-- Each worker, in its own txn:
UPDATE jobs SET status='RUNNING', worker=:id
WHERE id IN (
  SELECT id FROM jobs
  WHERE status='PENDING'
  ORDER BY created_at
  FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED      -- skip rows other workers locked
  LIMIT 10
)
RETURNING *;
\`\`\`

\`\`\`mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  participant W1 as Worker 1
  participant Q as jobs table
  participant W2 as Worker 2
  W1->>Q: SELECT ... FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED LIMIT 10
  Note over Q: rows 1-10 locked by W1
  W2->>Q: SELECT ... FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED LIMIT 10
  Note over Q: rows 1-10 skipped, W2 gets 11-20
  W1->>Q: UPDATE status=DONE; COMMIT
  W2->>Q: UPDATE status=DONE; COMMIT
\`\`\`

> [!TIP]
> SKIP LOCKED turns the database into a contention-free competing-consumers queue: workers never block each other and never grab the same job. NOWAIT (error if locked) and the default (wait) are the other two FOR UPDATE wait modes — know all three.

## Mapping to Spring @Transactional

\`\`\`java
@Transactional(isolation = Isolation.SERIALIZABLE,
               propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED,
               timeout = 5, readOnly = false)
public void transfer(long from, long to, long cents) { ... }
\`\`\`

**Isolation** maps directly to the JDBC connection's isolation level. **Propagation** controls how nested @Transactional methods compose:

| Propagation | Behavior |
|---|---|
| **REQUIRED** (default) | join existing txn, else start one |
| **REQUIRES_NEW** | always start a new txn, suspend the outer one |
| **NESTED** | savepoint inside the outer txn (partial rollback) |
| **MANDATORY** | must already be in a txn, else error |
| **SUPPORTS** | join if present, else run non-transactionally |
| **NOT_SUPPORTED** | suspend any txn, run non-transactionally |
| **NEVER** | error if a txn exists |

> [!WARNING]
> Classic Spring traps interviewers probe:
> - **Self-invocation**: calling another @Transactional method on \`this\` bypasses the proxy → no new transaction. The annotation is honored only through the Spring-managed bean.
> - **Checked exceptions don't roll back by default** — only RuntimeException/Error do. Use \`rollbackFor = Exception.class\` for checked ones.
> - **readOnly=true** is a hint: it can let the driver/Hibernate skip dirty-checking and route to replicas, but it does NOT make the DB reject writes by itself.
> - **REQUIRES_NEW holds two connections** at once (outer suspended, inner active) — pool-exhaustion risk in loops.

> [!SUCCESS]
> Put the retry-on-40001 loop **outside** the @Transactional boundary — a retry must start a brand-new transaction. A common bug is retrying inside the same transaction that already failed, which can't succeed. Use Spring Retry (\`@Retryable\`) on the calling method, or a wrapping loop that re-invokes the transactional bean.
`,
