            title: `Read Scaling: Replicas, Replication Lag & Caching`,
            notes: `# Read Scaling

Most OLTP systems are **read-heavy** (often 90%+ reads). The first scaling lever is offloading reads from the primary to **read replicas**, with caches in front.

## Streaming replication

The primary ships its **WAL** to replicas, which replay it to stay (nearly) current. Replicas are read-only (\`hot_standby\`) and serve queries.

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart TB
  App[Application / Read-Write Router] -->|writes + read-your-writes| P[(Primary)]
  App -->|stale-tolerant reads| LB{Read Load Balancer}
  P -- WAL stream --> R1[(Replica 1)]
  P -- WAL stream --> R2[(Replica 2)]
  P -- WAL stream --> R3[(Replica 3 / analytics)]
  LB --> R1
  LB --> R2
  LB --> R3
  R1 -. promote on failover .-> P
\`\`\`

## Synchronous vs asynchronous replication

| | Asynchronous | Synchronous (\`synchronous_commit=on\` + \`synchronous_standby_names\`) |
|---|---|---|
| COMMIT returns | After primary fsyncs WAL locally | After ≥1 standby confirms receipt/flush |
| Data loss on primary failure | Possible (un-shipped WAL lost) | Zero acknowledged-commit loss |
| Write latency | Low | Higher (network RTT to standby per commit) |
| Throughput | High | Lower |
| If standby is down | Primary keeps accepting writes | Primary **blocks** writes (unless quorum/extra standbys) |
| Use for | Read scaling, geo replicas, most replicas | Financial/RPO=0 requirements |

> [!WARNING]
> Naive synchronous replication couples primary availability to standby availability — lose the sync standby and writes stall. Use \`synchronous_standby_names\` with quorum (e.g. \`ANY 1 (s1, s2, s3)\`) so any one of several can ack. \`remote_write\` vs \`remote_apply\` levels trade durability for latency.

## Replication lag & read-your-writes

Async replicas are **eventually consistent**. Lag (ms to seconds, more under load or long-running queries on the replica) means: **a user writes to the primary, then reads from a replica and doesn't see their own write.** This breaks the **read-your-writes** guarantee and produces "I saved it but it's gone" bugs.

Mitigations:
1. **Route the writing user's subsequent reads to the primary** for a short window (sticky to primary after write).
2. **Causal / LSN tracking**: capture the WAL **LSN** at write time; on read, pick a replica whose \`replay_lsn ≥ that LSN\`, or wait. Postgres exposes \`pg_current_wal_lsn()\` / \`pg_last_wal_replay_lsn()\`.
3. **Read from primary for read-after-write critical paths** (e.g. "confirm order" page); send only stale-tolerant traffic (search, listings, analytics) to replicas.
4. Cap/monitor lag; **evict replicas exceeding a lag threshold** from the read pool.

> [!DANGER]
> Don't blindly send all reads to replicas. Classify each read: *can it tolerate staleness?* Account balances, post-write confirmations, and uniqueness checks usually cannot. Search results, feeds, and reports usually can. Getting this wrong is a correctness bug, not a perf issue.

## Load-balancing reads

- App-level routing (separate read/write DataSources; Spring \`@Transactional(readOnly=true)\` routing via \`AbstractRoutingDataSource\`).
- A proxy (PgPool-II, HAProxy, ProxySQL for MySQL) that splits reads/writes.
- Cloud reader endpoints (Aurora reader endpoint, RDS read replica DNS).

> [!TIP]
> Keep one replica out of the user-facing read pool dedicated to **heavy analytics / reporting**. A long analytical query on a replica can stall WAL replay (\`max_standby_streaming_delay\`), spiking lag for everyone else. Isolate it.

## Caching layers (Redis) & invalidation

A cache (Redis/Memcached) in front of the DB absorbs the hottest reads at sub-ms latency and shields the DB.

**Patterns:**
- **Cache-aside (lazy)**: app checks cache; on miss, reads DB and populates cache. Most common.
- **Read-through / write-through**: cache library owns DB access.
- **Write-behind**: write to cache, async flush to DB (risk of loss).

**Invalidation** — "the second hard thing":
- **TTL** (expiry) — simplest, bounded staleness, no consistency guarantee.
- **Write-time invalidation** — delete/update the key on write. Prefer **delete over update** (avoids race where two writers leave a stale value).
- **Versioned keys** — embed an entity version in the key; bump version = instant invalidation of all derived keys.

> [!WARNING]
> Beware the **thundering herd / cache stampede**: a hot key expires and thousands of requests simultaneously hit the DB to recompute it. Mitigate with a per-key recompute **mutex/lock** (single-flight), **probabilistic early expiration**, or serving slightly stale data while one worker refreshes.

> [!DANGER]
> Cache + DB is a **dual-write**: update DB and cache as two steps and a crash between them leaves them inconsistent. Safer: write DB, then **delete** the cache key (cache-aside repopulates on next read). For strong needs, drive invalidation off the DB's change stream (CDC/logical decoding) so the cache follows committed data.

## Materialized views

A **materialized view** stores the *result* of an expensive query physically. Great for dashboards/aggregations that are read constantly but tolerate staleness.

- \`REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW\` recomputes; \`REFRESH ... CONCURRENTLY\` avoids locking readers (requires a unique index).
- Trade-off: data is **as fresh as the last refresh**. Schedule refreshes or trigger off events.
- Not a substitute for an index — they don't auto-update.

> [!SUCCESS]
> The layered read-scaling strategy: index well → replicas for read fan-out → Redis for the hottest keys → materialized views for expensive aggregations. Each layer trades a little freshness for a lot of throughput; choose per access pattern.`,
