            title: `Write Scaling & Table Partitioning`,
            notes: `# Write Scaling & Partitioning

Replicas scale **reads** but not **writes** — every write still funnels through the single primary. When the primary's write throughput, table size, or maintenance windows become the limit, you scale vertically first, then partition, then (last resort) shard.

## Vertical limits

Vertical scaling (bigger box, faster NVMe, more RAM) is the **first** move — it's cheap engineering vs sharding. But it hits ceilings:
- A single primary's CPU/IOPS cap.
- **Huge tables** (billions of rows): index maintenance, VACUUM, and bloat get painful; B-tree depth grows; a full table rewrite/ALTER becomes a multi-hour outage.
- One giant table = one giant VACUUM, one giant index, one lock.

> [!TIP]
> Many teams think they need sharding when they actually need **partitioning + a bigger box + better indexes**. Partitioning solves the *single huge table* problem without the operational nightmare of distributing data across nodes.

## Declarative partitioning

Postgres **declarative partitioning** splits one logical table into physical **partitions**, each a real table holding a subset of rows. The parent is empty; rows live in partitions. Strategies:

| Strategy | Partition by | Good for | Example |
|---|---|---|---|
| **RANGE** | A range of values | Time-series, sequential IDs | by month on \`created_at\` |
| **LIST** | Explicit value sets | Categorical / tenant region | by \`region IN ('EU','US')\` |
| **HASH** | hash(key) mod N | Even distribution, no natural range | hash of \`customer_id\` into 16 |

\`\`\`sql
CREATE TABLE events (id bigint, created_at timestamptz, payload jsonb)
  PARTITION BY RANGE (created_at);

CREATE TABLE events_2026_06 PARTITION OF events
  FOR VALUES FROM ('2026-06-01') TO ('2026-07-01');
\`\`\`

## Partition pruning — the payoff

The planner **prunes** (skips) partitions that can't match the query's predicate. A query \`WHERE created_at >= '2026-06-10'\` only touches \`events_2026_06\` (and later), ignoring 50 other monthly partitions. This is the main performance win: smaller indexes scanned, less I/O.

> [!WARNING]
> Pruning only works if the query **filters on the partition key**. \`WHERE user_id = 42\` on a table partitioned by \`created_at\` scans **every** partition (worse than an unpartitioned table). Choose the partition key to match your dominant query predicate, or you lose the benefit and add overhead.

Pruning happens at **plan time** (constant predicates) and **execution time** (parameters, joins). Verify with \`EXPLAIN\` — you want only the relevant partitions in the plan.

## Operational wins of partitioning

- **Cheap archival/retention**: drop old data with \`DROP TABLE events_2025_01\` or \`DETACH PARTITION\` — instant metadata operation, no giant \`DELETE\` + VACUUM bloat. This alone justifies time partitioning for logs/events.
- **Per-partition maintenance**: VACUUM/REINDEX/ANALYZE one partition at a time; smaller, faster, less locking.
- **Smaller, hotter indexes**: the "current month" index fits in cache; old partitions sit cold.

> [!SUCCESS]
> For append-heavy time-series (logs, events, metrics, orders), RANGE-by-time partitioning + automated partition creation + DROP-based retention is the canonical pattern. It turns expensive bulk DELETEs into instant DROPs and keeps the working set small.

## Gotchas

> [!DANGER]
> - **Unique constraints / PKs must include the partition key** (or be globally enforced at the app level) — Postgres can't enforce a global unique index across partitions unless the column is part of the key.
> - **Too many partitions** (thousands) inflates planning time and catalog bloat; keep partition counts reasonable (tens to low hundreds typically).
> - You must **create future partitions ahead of time** (cron/pg_partman) or inserts for new periods fail with "no partition found."
> - Cross-partition queries that can't prune fan out to all partitions.

## Partitioning vs sharding (don't confuse them)

| | Partitioning | Sharding |
|---|---|---|
| Where | Within **one** database instance | Across **many** independent instances |
| Scales | Manageability, maintenance, query pruning | **Write throughput + storage** beyond one node |
| Transactions | Normal ACID across partitions | Cross-shard = hard (no easy global txn) |
| Complexity | Low (declarative DDL) | High (routing, rebalancing, ops) |

Partitioning does **not** scale writes beyond a single node — all partitions share the same primary's CPU/IO. It's a prerequisite skill and often the right answer before sharding.`,
