            title: `NoSQL & Polyglot Persistence: CAP, BASE & CQRS`,
            notes: `# NoSQL & Polyglot Persistence

Relational is the default for good reasons (ACID, joins, mature tooling, strong consistency). But certain access patterns and scale points make a relational DB the wrong tool. **Polyglot persistence** = using the right store per workload, accepting the operational cost of running several.

## NoSQL families & when each fits

| Family | Model | Sweet spot | Examples |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Key-Value** | opaque value by key | Sessions, caches, feature flags, simple lookups at huge scale | Redis, DynamoDB, Riak |
| **Document** | JSON-ish documents | Flexible/evolving schema, aggregate-per-document, content | MongoDB, Couchbase, DynamoDB |
| **Wide-Column** | rows with dynamic column families, partition+clustering keys | Massive write throughput, time-series, known query patterns | Cassandra, ScyllaDB, HBase, Bigtable |
| **Graph** | nodes + edges | Relationship-heavy traversals (social, fraud, recommendations) | Neo4j, JanusGraph, Neptune |
| **Time-Series** | timestamped metrics | Metrics, IoT, observability, downsampling/retention | TimescaleDB, InfluxDB, Prometheus |
| **Search** | inverted index | Full-text search, faceting, relevance ranking | Elasticsearch, OpenSearch |

> [!TIP]
> The senior framing: don't ask "SQL or NoSQL?" Ask "**what is the access pattern, consistency requirement, and scale?**" Cassandra is brilliant for high-write time-series with known queries and disastrous for ad-hoc analytical joins. Choose the store the *queries* demand.

## SQL vs NoSQL — the real trade-offs

| | Relational (SQL) | NoSQL (varies) |
|---|---|---|
| Schema | Fixed, enforced, migrations | Flexible / schema-on-read |
| Joins | First-class | Usually none (denormalize / app-side) |
| Consistency | Strong ACID by default | Often eventual (tunable) |
| Scaling writes | Vertical / shard (hard) | Horizontal, built-in (often) |
| Query flexibility | Ad-hoc, rich SQL | Optimized for designed access patterns |
| Modeling driver | Normalize around data | Denormalize around queries |

> [!WARNING]
> NoSQL "flexible schema" is not "no schema" — it's **schema-on-read**: the schema moves into your application code and every reader must handle every historical shape. And many NoSQL stores require you to **model around your queries up front** (Cassandra: one table per query pattern). You trade migration pain for query rigidity.

## CAP & PACELC

**CAP**: under a network **P**artition, a distributed store must choose **C**onsistency (reject/stale-block to stay consistent) or **A**vailability (serve possibly-stale data). You can't have both during a partition. **PACELC** extends it: **E**lse (no partition), you still trade **L**atency vs **C**onsistency.

- CP systems (e.g. HBase, Spanner-ish, MongoDB w/ majority): prefer correctness, may reject writes during partition.
- AP systems (e.g. Cassandra, DynamoDB default): stay available, reconcile later.

> [!TIP]
> Real systems are **tunable**, not binary. Cassandra/Dynamo let you pick consistency **per operation** via quorums: with replication factor N, if **R + W > N** you get strong consistency for that read/write; relax for latency/availability. Know this — interviewers love "how would you get read-your-writes on Cassandra?" (answer: \`QUORUM\` reads+writes with R+W>N, or \`LOCAL_QUORUM\` per-DC).

## BASE vs ACID

**BASE** = **B**asically **A**vailable, **S**oft state, **E**ventually consistent — the NoSQL philosophy opposite ACID. Accept temporary inconsistency for availability/scale, converge over time. Fine for feeds, counters, catalogs; **not** for money, inventory you can oversell, or uniqueness you must enforce.

## The dual-write problem

The crux of polyglot persistence: keeping **two stores consistent** when one write must update both (e.g. write to Postgres **and** index in Elasticsearch, or update DB **and** publish a Kafka event).

> [!DANGER]
> A naive dual write — \`db.save(); search.index();\` — has no atomicity. A crash or failure between the two leaves them **permanently inconsistent**, and you can't wrap a relational DB and an external system in one transaction. This is one of the most common distributed-data bugs.

**Solutions:**
- **Transactional Outbox**: in the same DB transaction, write the business row **and** an \`outbox\` row. A separate relay reads the outbox (poll or **CDC**) and publishes/indexes. The DB transaction guarantees both-or-neither; the relay guarantees at-least-once delivery downstream.
- **Change Data Capture (CDC)** (Debezium reading the WAL/binlog): the DB's commit log *is* the source of truth; downstream stores (search, cache, read models) follow it. No second write in the app at all.
- **Sagas** for multi-service workflows: a sequence of local transactions with compensating actions on failure.

\`\`\`mermaid
flowchart LR
  W[Write request] --> TX[(Postgres TX)]
  TX -->|same transaction| BIZ[business row]
  TX -->|same transaction| OB[outbox row]
  REL[Relay / Debezium CDC] -->|reads committed outbox / WAL| OB
  REL --> K[(Kafka)]
  K --> ES[Elasticsearch index]
  K --> CACHE[Redis read model]
  K --> RM[CQRS read DB]
\`\`\`

## CQRS read models

**CQRS** (Command Query Responsibility Segregation) splits the **write model** (normalized, transactional, optimized for commands) from one or more **read models** (denormalized, optimized for specific queries), kept in sync via events/CDC.

- Writes go to the authoritative store (e.g. Postgres). Events flow out (outbox/CDC).
- Read models are **purpose-built per query**: an Elasticsearch index for search, a Redis projection for a dashboard, a denormalized table for a screen.
- Read models are **eventually consistent** with the write model — embrace it for the read side, keep the write side strongly consistent.

> [!SUCCESS]
> Polyglot done right: **Postgres as the system of record** (ACID for the business invariants) + **derived read stores** (search, cache, analytics) fed by **CDC/outbox events**, not by app-level dual writes. One source of truth, many query-optimized projections, no dual-write corruption.

> [!EU]
> Polyglot multiplies where personal data lives — every derived store (search index, cache, analytics, read model) is also in scope for GDPR. A "delete my data" (right to erasure) request must propagate to **all** projections, not just the system of record. Track data lineage and make deletes flow through the same event pipeline that built the read models.`,
