            title: `Caching: 1st-Level, 2nd-Level & Query Cache`,
            notes: `## Three caches, three very different lifetimes

| Cache | Scope | Shared? | Holds | Default |
|-------|-------|---------|-------|---------|
| **1st-level** (persistence context) | One \`Session\`/tx | No | Managed entity instances | Always on, can't disable |
| **2nd-level (L2)** | \`SessionFactory\` (app-wide) | Yes (across tx/threads) | Entity state (dehydrated), collections | Off by default |
| **Query cache** | \`SessionFactory\` | Yes | Query result *id lists* + timestamps | Off; requires L2 |

> [!TIP]
> The 1st-level cache gives you the **identity guarantee** and dirty checking; it is not optional and not configurable. The L2 cache is what people mean by "Hibernate caching" — it's opt-in, per-entity, and easy to misuse.

### 2nd-level cache

L2 stores a **dehydrated** form of entity state (not the object graph) keyed by id, in a provider like **EHCache**, **Caffeine (JCache)**, **Infinispan**, or **Redis** (via JCache). On a \`find()\` miss in L1, Hibernate checks L2 before hitting the DB.

\`\`\`java
@Entity
@Cacheable
@org.hibernate.annotations.Cache(usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE)
public class Country { @Id String iso; String name; }
\`\`\`

> [!WARNING]
> L2 caches by **primary key**. It accelerates \`find(id)\` and \`@ManyToOne\` navigation — it does **not** cache arbitrary queries (that's the *query cache*). A \`select ... where name = ?\` still hits the DB even if every row is in L2.

### Cache concurrency strategies

| Strategy | Use when | Locking behavior |
|----------|----------|------------------|
| \`READ_ONLY\` | Data never changes after insert (reference data, currencies) | No locks; fastest; update throws |
| \`NONSTRICT_READ_WRITE\` | Rare updates, brief staleness tolerable | Invalidates entry on update (no lock); small stale window |
| \`READ_WRITE\` | Concurrent updates, need consistency | Soft locks entries during update; async; uses timestamps |
| \`TRANSACTIONAL\` | Need full XA/JTA consistency | Provider participates in JTA transaction; heavier |

> [!SUCCESS]
> Pick the **weakest strategy that's correct**: READ_ONLY for immutable reference data is dramatically cheaper than READ_WRITE.

### Query cache

\`\`\`java
em.createQuery("select c from Country c where c.continent = :x")
  .setParameter("x", "EU")
  .setHint("org.hibernate.cacheable", true)
  .getResultList();
\`\`\`

The query cache stores the **list of entity ids** the query returned, plus an update-timestamp per table. It does *not* store entity data (that comes from L2).

> [!DANGER]
> The query cache is **invalidated by any write to the involved tables** via the \`UpdateTimestampsCache\`. On a write-heavy table the query cache is constantly invalidated and can be *slower* than no cache (extra bookkeeping + frequent misses). Only cache queries over rarely-changing tables.

### When L2 helps vs hurts

> [!SUCCESS] Helps
> - Read-heavy, small, slowly-changing reference data (countries, currencies, config, product catalog).
> - High \`find(id)\` / \`@ManyToOne\` navigation rates.
> - Multi-node only with a **distributed/invalidating** provider (Infinispan/Redis) — otherwise nodes go stale.

> [!DANGER] Hurts
> - Write-heavy entities → constant invalidation, lock overhead, low hit rate.
> - Large entities / huge tables → memory pressure, GC, eviction churn.
> - Multi-node with a **local** cache (EHCache local) and no invalidation → **stale reads** across instances.
> - Bulk JPQL/HQL \`UPDATE\`/\`DELETE\` **bypass L2** and leave it stale (see §5/§6).

### Cache invalidation

- Entity changes through the session auto-update L2.
- **Bulk** \`update Order o set ...\` HQL does **not** touch L2 — you must evict: \`em.getEntityManagerFactory().getCache().evict(Order.class)\` or use \`@org.hibernate.annotations.NaturalIdCache\`/region eviction.
- Native SQL updates Hibernate doesn't know about → manual eviction or query-space declaration.`,
